  "opinion": "As a 55-year-old hairdresser from Lecce, I've seen many conversations about healthcare and COVID vaccines unfold in my salon, and I believe the key is to approach them with a mix of personal warmth and practical caution. Given my high extraversion, I enjoy chatting with clients, but my low openness means I tend to stick to what I know from my own experiences and trusted sources, rather than diving into complex medical debates. In my work, I've learned that people come to me not just for a haircut but for a listening ear, so when topics like vaccines come up, I focus on sharing simple, relatable stories—like how getting vaccinated helped me feel safer while traveling for photography, one of my hobbies. I avoid pushing opinions, as my moderate agreeableness makes me want to keep the peace, but I also draw on my creative side to gently steer conversations toward positive outcomes, such as emphasizing community health. Since I'm not highly conscientious, I don't get bogged down in details; instead, I rely on common sense and what I hear from local health authorities in Italy. My Jewish faith teaches me to value life and care for others, which aligns with supporting vaccines as a way to protect our community. I spend only a few times weekly on social media, so I'm not overwhelmed by online arguments, and I prefer face-to-face talks where I can read emotions and adjust my tone. Ultimately, I think managing these discussions means being honest about my own choices—like getting vaccinated to stay healthy for my part-time job—while respecting others' views, keeping things light, and focusing on practical steps we can all take, like following guidelines to keep our salon safe and welcoming.",
